Title : Gordon Campbell (cricketer)
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}
{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}
'''Gordon Cathcart Campbell''' (4 June 1885 â€“ 13 August 1961) was an [[Australian (people)|Australian]] [[cricket]]er active from 1909 to 1915 who played for [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]]. 
 
Campbell was born in [[Myrtle Bank, South Australia]] and died in [[Woodville South, South Australia]]. He appeared in 23 [[first-class cricket|first-class matches]] as a right-handed [[batting (cricket)|batsman]] who [[wicketkeeper|kept wicket]]. He scored 497 [[run (cricket)|runs]] with a highest score of 43 and held 28 catches with 20 stumpings.

He toured North America with an Australian team from May to September 1913, a tour of 54 matches including five first-class matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/5/Australia_in_North_America_1913.html| title = Australia in North America 1913| publisher = CricketArchive| accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref> He was selected in the Australian team which was to tour South Africa in 1914-15 as one of the two wicket-keepers, as well as the manager and third selector;<ref>{{cite news|title=Team for South Africa. A Strong Side.|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15517999|accessdate=19 November 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=22 June 1914|ref=p. 9}}</ref> but war prevented the tour.

During the [[World War I|First World War]], he served in the [[First Australian Imperial Force]] (1st AIF) with the rank of [[major]] and, after the war ended, Campbell was appointed by the [[Cricket Australia|Australian Board of (Cricket) Control]] as its representative in dealings with the AIF Sports Control Board about the proposed AIF team which was formed out of military personnel as the [[Australian Imperial Force Touring XI]].

